A new course at Harvard University this year allows all of its undergraduate students to get more sleep in an effort to counteract the growing macho culture of studying by caffeinated 'all-night sessions'.
An academic has found that students at the world's top university are often unaware when it comes to the basics of how to look after themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the U.S.
He was inspired to start the course after he gave a talk about the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of it, one girl approached me and said, 'Why are they telling me this now, in my senior year?'
She said that no one has told her how important sleep is - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, offered for the first time this year, explains to students the basic principles of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as how it improves their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after it was found that students were seriously asleep during the week.
The hour-long course involves a couple of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a dormitory, where students need to click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes, and books to be told about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation and the importance of a sleep-time routine.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know this won't change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know - just as you have the right to know what the health impact of choosing to smoke cigarettes is," added Prof Czeisler.
The culture of pride to "study all night" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students has meant that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
To make sure you get enough good quality sleep, a student's "secret weapon" should be to avoid stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said - even to avoid it from putting on weight, because sleep deprivation puts the brain in a starvation mode, which makes you feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after running one of his classes during his first year at Harvard last year.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to pursue a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the institution where people compete with each other.
Prof Czeisler recommended that students should consider setting an alarm for when they are going to sleep, as well as when to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm and cause you to struggle.
